  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concern—it's a lived reality for many students and professionals who face unconscious biases that undermine their performance. As a nurse with a background in healthcare, I've seen how these psychological barriers manifest in clinical settings, and I've come to understand that the same dynamics play out in STEM fields. When someone internalizes the belief that their group is less capable in a particular domain, their performance can suffer, even if they're equally skilled. For instance, a woman in a physics class might tense up during an exam because she's worried about confirming stereotypes about her gender and intelligence. This isn't about individual failure—it's about systemic issues that need addressing. The question isn't whether we should address it, but how. I believe the solution lies in creating inclusive environments where everyone feels seen and valued. In my work, I've seen the power of mentorship and culturally responsive teaching to help students feel more confident. By integrating diverse role models into curricula and fostering open dialogues about bias, we can shift the narrative from 'you're not good enough' to 'your potential is limitless.' It's important to acknowledge that addressing stereotype threat requires sustained effort and collaboration across disciplines. As someone who values empathy and community—both of which are central to my nursing practice—I'm convinced that when we prioritize psychological safety and equitable opportunities, we don't just improve STEM outcomes; we build a more just and innovative society. After all, in healthcare, we treat the whole person, not just the symptoms. The same principle should guide our approach to STEM education.",
